article.description:
Jason Richardson had 23 points and seven
rebounds in his return after missing four games with a sore back, leading the Warriors to a 109-77 win over the slumping Timberwolves.
article.headline: Richardson's return keys Warriors rout of Wolves
article.linkText: Richardson's return keys Warriors rout of Wolves
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Jason Richardson couldn't sit on the bench and watch the Warriors struggle for another moment. It was a good thing he came back for Golden State because Baron Davis went down. Richardson had 23 points and seven rebounds in his return after missing four games with a sore back, and the Warriors beat the Minnesota Timberwolves 109-77 on Saturday night. Davis, Golden State's point guard and second-leading scorer behind Richardson, tweaked his left ankle at the shootaround earlier in the day and Mike Dunleavy got the start in his place after being scheduled to come off the bench for the first time all season. Davis still played 20 minutes and had six assists, five rebounds and two points, but he's uncertain whether he will ready for Monday's home game against Denver. "Not good at all, man," Davis said of the ankle, which he hurt when he came down on a coach's foot after a layin. "It's nothing severe, though. It's something where I've got to get therapy and treatment and get that strength back." Troy Murphy added 20 points, eight rebounds and four assists in three quarters and Dunleavy had 14 points, six rebounds and four assists for Golden State, which had lost its last two to Minnesota at home. Minnesota had won five of the previous seven meetings between the clubs on the Warriors' home floor. "I think we were desperate," Warriors coach Mike Montgomery said. "That's the way we've got to play every night. We don't have much margin for error." Kevin Garnett had 15 points and 11 rebounds for his 32nd double-double of the season, a night after getting 27 points and 15 boards in a loss at Portland. Ricky Davis scored 20 points and had five rebounds in Minnesota's worst loss of the season. Richardson made his first two field-goal tries, pounded an acrobatic one-handed slam midway through the second quarter and hit a 3 a couple of minutes later that put Golden State on the way to a big lead it never relinquished. "It felt good to finally get up and get the dunk in," said Richardson, whose Adrenalin kept him from noticing any problems with his back. "That's the most I've done since I got injured. I hope I don't feel it tomorrow." Mickael Pietrus had 17 points and six rebounds and rookie Ike Diogu scored 10 of his 12 points in the fourth quarter for the Warriors, who had lost six of seven and 10 of 14 at home after an 89-86 loss Thursday to the San Antonio Spurs. The Timberwolves, averaging 16 turnovers in their previous five games, lost their third straight and seventh in nine overall and fourth in a row on the road. They conclude this four-game road trip Monday night at Phoenix. Minnesota shot 37.6 percent and had a scoreless stretch of 5:24 spanning halftime and lost for the 13th time in its last 15 road games. The Timberwolves allowed nearly as many points in three quarters Saturday (85) as they did in the entire game in their 89-85 loss at Portland on Friday. First-year coach Dwane Casey is still working to get his team in sync after the seven-player trade Jan. 26 with Boston that sent popular forward Wally Szczerbiak to the Celtics in the deal that brought Davis to Minnesota. Casey liked how his team played early, but the Timberwolves struggled to maintain that consistency. "We just couldn't regroup and then they got on a roll," Casey said. "The more we tried, the more they got on a roll and got going, so there's no answer. If you don't come out with a focus and effort for 48 minutes in this league, you're in trouble." The Warriors made nine of their first 17 shots, while the Timberwolves started the game 7-of-13. But Minnesota then went 9-for-36 the rest of the way and didn't score during the final 4:21 of the second quarter to fall behind 56-37 at halftime.

Game notes
Montgomery said he had decided not to start Dunleavy just "to make a change" and didn't say whether Dunleavy or Pietrus would start in the small forward spot Monday. ... Golden State G Derek Fisher, who missed Friday's practice to attend to a family matter, was scheduled to return early in the first quarter Saturday, but was delayed and showed for the start of the second quarter. ... Richardson did some running and other work Friday and wasn't sore Saturday, showing himself and the Warriors' training staff he was ready to get back on the court. "The doctors say he's OK to go, the trainer says he's OK to go and he says he's OK to go," Montgomery said. "You don't put a guy out there with a restriction." ... Golden State was the last Western Conference team the Timberwolves hadn't yet played. ... Minnesota is 7-17 away from the Target Center. ... The Warriors drew 20,023 for their ninth sellout.
